title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger MkIII 22/45 $275
postcontent:
Ruger MkIII 22/45

Will take pics and send to interested parties upon request. 

This piece comes from a long history of Ruger excellence and reliability.  Many people use these in competition target shooting.  When the Navy SEALs wanted a .22LR pistol for “up close and personal” work, they chose a suppressed Ruger MkII, the previous version of the MkIII.

The “improvements” from the MkII to the MkIII consist of a magazine disconnect and loaded chamber indicator (both of which some people remove).  I had the magazine disconnect removed to see how it changed the piece; the trigger was smoother, magazines dropped more freely, and disassembly and reassembly were easier.  But the disconnect has been reinstalled for the purpose of selling the piece.  If you want it removed, I suggest either the Tandemkross or Volquartsen MkII hammer bushing – really easy fix, with plenty of help on the internet.

The 22/45 was designed to match the grip angle and controls of the 1911.  This 22/45 is the Target version with bull barrel, which makes a VERY stable shooting platform.  This provides excellent experience for new shooters to learn basics before moving to more powerful handguns.  If you are shooting any handgun before you learn with a .22LR, somebody steered you WRONG and set you up to be “recoil sensitive” and therefore less capable of rapid target reacquisition after the first shot.  Training with this piece, putting all 10 rounds into a small group very quickly, can set you up to shoot more powerful handguns effectively for self-defense.  

I bought this new but just don’t need it anymore.  It shows the wear I have given it, but it is in excellent condition.  It comes with the original box and paperwork – everything except that stupid padlock (which was quickly reassigned to another use).  But this piece has an internal key so you can lock the safety in the Safe position – far better than risking damage to the action with a padlock.  I also will include a Ruger branded leather holster – fits the piece perfectly.

The price is $275 firm – that’s what this is worth.

I will only deal FTF, with a SC resident with CWP or FFL.

title: For Trade:  Your time and Consideration of The ATF's action on M855 Ball
postcontent:
For all enthusiasts: sporting, collecting or otherwise, please take note of the proposed rule-making from the BATFE concerning M855 ball ammo. I have seen some interesting advertisements in the last couple of days written by those who claim interest in free market economics. While I believe in healthy economic competition, I don't care for those who would divert fellow enthusiasts time and attention from the facts and instead seek to gain monetarily from the circumstances. If those parties interested in the free market were genuine wouldn't it be far more productive to halt the construction of an artificial market created by government regulations instead of exploiting the situation?  I would like you to turn your attention to this link so you may judge for yourself given the facts and more importantly that there is still time to do something about this. 

http://www.atf.gov/sites/default/files/assets/Library/Notices/atf_framework_for_determining_whether_certain_projectiles_are_primarily_intended_for_sporting_purposes.pdf

March 16th is fast approaching so please read and make your comments to the BATFE. 

Thank you.
